@hasonguo It uses `flutter_isolate` in the background, it just adds an extra layer to make handling isolates (any isolates, actually) easier by adding the boilerplate for communication so that you don't need to set it up manually every time. It used a different way of addressing the issue earlier, but that was rendered impossible by changes in Flutter itself, and was changed to rely on `flutter_isolate` instead.

We're going in circles. Yes, there are solutions, **both plugins actually.** As Ryan pointed out, there is an overhead involved in making the channel communications possible. More likely than not, it's exactly this overhead that made the Flutter team avoid adding it automatically to the original `Isolate`, as you don't need the support in many (most?) cases.

Still, it's not as clean a solution as it could get. If the Flutter team would be able to provide channel communication without the overhead, directly and automatically, right out of the box with any basic `Isolate`, the whole discussion would be moot. However, the opposite also holds true: they are not really pursuing change for the sake of change. If there is a viable solution in a package or plugin, why spend time and add weight to the core?

@aytunch Considering that nothing has changed since, I won't refrain from suggesting two plugins (one of which I'm a maintainer of but it actually relies on the other one to do that part of the heavy lifting):

https://pub.dev/packages/flutter_isolate
https://pub.dev/packages/isolate_handler

@aytunch if I were making that project today I'd either:
1) Issue the information to encode via a platform channel to the native code and call ffmpeg from there.
1) Use ffmpeg_kit_flutter from a background isolate but use dart [ports](https://api.dart.dev/stable/2.15.1/dart-isolate/SendPort-class.html) to communicate with that isolate instead of platform channels.

@gaaclarke  thank you for the insight into how to handle this currently. we are all looking for the ability to do background processing (to keep our FPS at 60+). IMO all these limitations with isolates will cause more bugs than just giving us typical threads. why? we cannot do all background work in elegant steps. instead I have to shuffle data between isolates and maintain the state of my process. the limitation of shared memory is a mistake. the limitation of not using plugins is even more painful. so instead of keeping our background processing clean, I'm now forced to do several work arounds. 

i'm building a messaging app. I need to be able to encrypt and send over the network. I need to be able to receive messages, decrypt, and present. I created an isolate pool to receive messages. I'm now re-designing the app to work around all the isolate limitations. I need extra queues, extra state, and moving data from isolates to main. 

Good luck everyone! Cheers.

> IMO all these limitations with isolates will cause more bugs than just giving us typical threads. why? we cannot do all background work in elegant steps.

@j3g IMO I would contend that you are _avoiding_ alot of potential bugs by not having to do all the **required** work yourself to *safely* use shared mutable state from multiple threads.
I'm also not clear as to how the limitation of not being able to call platform channels from non-main isolates affects your use case of needing to decrypt messages off the main isolate?

Thread-safe data types are your friend. I've never had threading issues, because I follow thread-safe design patterns. Because I'm a season developer I don't need artificial limitations for "safety". I would argue that because of isolate limitations, I am forced to add a lot of extra code to get things done. All that extra code gives more probability of bugs. My code is clean and sequential with threads, but more complex with isolates.

For Example. Why am I on this discussion? Because my flutter app crashes from the generic error **“Exception: Null check operator used on a null value”**. I figured out it happens when I tried to call my plugin within the isolate. I spent many hours troubleshooting thinking that it was my error. Now I discover it is yet another isolate limitation. I didn’t see this limitation in the official docs. So after today I will redesign my elegant code to something more complex...

@maks is there a forum I can go and discuss/learn further? i'm not finding quality on stackoverflow.

@j3g John, still, the question arises that why should each and every isolate make it possible to call platform channels when it comes with a cost. The cost is smaller with the changes than it was before, yes, but it's still a cost. If many isolates don't need that extra functionality, why would we accept the incurred costs?

In every single part of Flutter development we accept the fact that much of the important functionality comes in the form of plugins and packages, not in the core, for two reasons. One is to keep the engine as lean as possible (and it still isn't what I'd call lean, of course, in this day and age we and our users don't care that much whether an app is 1 MB or 20, but still). The other is to make sure a much larger community can build useful parts of the jigsaw puzzle and we don't need to wait for the engine team to deliver everything.

I came to be included in this channel-isolate story exactly for these reasons: I needed a solution to call a plugin. It didn't work out of the box, I looked around for solutions and found out that solutions _do_ exist. Not in the core Isolate but they exist. It just happened that the original creator of one of the plugins mentioned above asked me whether, for her lack of time to maintain it, I'd be interested in taking it over and I did. Part of the reason I said yes was that I used it in several apps and I would need to maintain my own version, anyway. It wasn't my original idea, I don't mention it from time to time because I want to take credit for it or brag about it but simply, as in many other areas of Flutter development, there _is_ a solution with the usual addition of a single line in `pubspec`. Only those need to use it who need it, the rest of the isolates will not suffer from the additional cost.

@mariopepe Yes, I know. I use isolates for similar purposes all the time. It's very easy to do and it works fine.

It's an awkward situation. I don't want to constantly advertise that I'm affiliated with the solution. It wasn't my invention, it's not part of my ego :-), I wast just an active user that needed it badly around the time when the original maintainer wanted to move on to other projects. There's no active development, it's on the back burner, it just works, that's all.

So, I don't want to advertise it actively. I just have the feeling, every time another post appears in this thread, that many who desperately ask for this functionality are not aware of the fact that it _is_ readily available, just that it isn't in core. There are many such things in the Flutter world, tons of packages that are readily availabe but not in core. Why is this one any different?

## Text Editing Movement Keys via Shortcuts

This is the first PR to start migrating text editing to use Actions.  See the [design doc](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1QaVIr1bbOWJGNyyNsB75sXgTDRMuxP268sLGTBNDut0/edit#) for the entire plan.

This PR focuses only on the arrow keys, including all modifier keys, but it also establishes the pattern for handling all keyboard, mouse, and touch events for text editing.

### Example

This example shows how to use an additional Shortcuts widget to override some default text editing keyboard shortcuts to have new behavior. Instead of moving the cursor, alt + up/down will change the focused widget.  See the [docs](https://master-api.flutter.dev/flutter/widgets/DefaultTextEditingShortcuts-class.html) for more examples.

```dart
@override
Widget build(BuildContext context) {
  // If using WidgetsApp or its descendents MaterialApp or CupertinoApp,
  // then DefaultTextEditingShortcuts is already being inserted into the
  // widget tree.
  return DefaultTextEditingShortcuts(
    child: Center(
      child: Shortcuts(
        shortcuts: const <ShortcutActivator, Intent>{
          SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.arrowDown, alt: true): NextFocusIntent(),
          SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.arrowUp, alt: true): PreviousFocusIntent(),
        },
        child: Column(
          children: const <Widget>[
            TextField(
              decoration: InputDecoration(
                hintText: 'alt + down moves to the next field.',
              ),
            ),
            TextField(
              decoration: InputDecoration(
                hintText: 'And alt + up moves to the previous.',
              ),
            ),
          ],
        ),
      ),
    ),
  );
}
```

### Issues

Partial fix for https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/75004.
Closes https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/76121

### Tests

  * Test that it's possible to remap a shortcut to a different shortcut's Intent.
  *  Test that's possible to write a custom Action to completely change a text editing Intent's behavior.
  * Update RenderEditable tests that relied on the keyboard and have them call new methods instead.

### Breaking changes
None.

@justinmc want to confirm that, if merged, this would allow us to override the arrow keys in shortcuts. We have the following code for a `ChatMessageComposer` widget which wraps a TextField. At the highest level, we've got the following shortcuts:

```dart
    return FocusableActionDetector(
      shortcuts: {
        LogicalKeySet(LogicalKeyboardKey.arrowDown):
            const ListViewSelectionIntent(ListViewSelectionOption.next),
        LogicalKeySet(LogicalKeyboardKey.arrowUp):
            const ListViewSelectionIntent(ListViewSelectionOption.prev),
        LogicalKeySet(LogicalKeyboardKey.tab):
            const ListViewSelectionIntent(ListViewSelectionOption.select),
        LogicalKeySet(LogicalKeyboardKey.enter):
            const ChatComposerIntent(ChatComposerAction.send),
      },
...
```

And our UI when mentioning a user looks like this:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/220686/106374525-73722900-635a-11eb-8251-2afdd95ab57a.png)

The tab key seems to work fine but the up/down arrow default handling isn't suppressed. Whenever a mention ListView is visible, we'd want the up/down arrow keys only to navigate the selected item.

Thanks!

@LongCatIsLooong RE https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/75032#discussion_r580704225, currently I'm asserting that the selection isn't null in all of these render editable methods.  Is that alright since https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/76573 seems to indicate that a null/invalid selection should be impossible long term, or should I just do nothing?

Also about your comments above on exposing TextSelection and changing it elsewhere (https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/75032#discussion_r580770371), I'm on board with the sentiment but I also am not quite sure how this should look.  I think this class does too many things right now.  It would be great if we could just have functions that take the needed metrics (selection and TextPainter?) and then return the new selection.  I'll keep thinking about how we can do this as we go forward.

I'll think about doing something like you mentioned in https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/75032#discussion_r580765707 as well as we go forward.  Originally I was happy to get away from the _handleMovement method, which was like hundreds of lines long and hard to understand, but this broken up way of doing things is repeating some code here and there.
